  "opinion": "As a delivery driver in Bologna who’s spent most of my life in this city, I’ve seen how health discussions, especially around vaccines, can get heated. My parents had very limited education, so I learned early on to listen more than to argue. I’ve always been a quiet person—my agreeableness score is low, but I value harmony in my family and community. When I see posts online about vaccines, I don’t engage much. I spend an hour a day on social media, but I focus on calming conversations, not fueling them. My neuroticism is high, so I get anxious when people argue, but I try to stay grounded by thinking about my children and the elderly in my neighborhood. I’ve seen how vaccines have helped my grandmother, who had a stroke, and I believe in science because it’s what saved her. I don’t want to be the person who spreads misinformation. When someone shares a post that seems wrong, I’ll gently say, 'I think this might not be accurate—I’ve seen how vaccines protect people like my mom who had cancer.' It’s important to be kind, even when you disagree. My hobbies—travel, photography, yoga—help me stay calm. I’ve taken photos of my neighbors getting vaccinated, and it reminds me that these conversations matter. I don’t want to be seen as a 'vaxer' or a 'vax-hater,' but I want to be a bridge between people. In a city like Bologna, where everyone knows each other, it’s easier to talk calmly than to shout. I think the key is to share personal stories, not facts, because that’s what builds trust. My children are older now, and they’ve been vaccinated, so I know it works. I’ll keep sharing these quiet moments to help people feel less alone in their concerns.",
